	<h3 class="fw-bold text-dark my-4">Relations between objects</h3>
	<p class="fs-5 fw-light w-sm-75">
		Relations between objects are created with the 'Collection' attribute.  
		Example: an Intervention object will have a 'Technician' attribute that allows selecting a technician from the same collection.  
		These relationships are also visible in the object detail view.  
		Thus, when a Technician object is linked to Interventions, the detail view of each Technician automatically displays their Interventions and allows entering a new one for that Technician.
	</p>

	<h3 class="fw-bold text-dark my-4">Queries</h3>
	<p class="fs-5 fw-light w-sm-75">
		Queries allow you to save selection criteria in order to obtain a filtered collection of objects that meet those criteria.
		<br><br>
		These Queries accept different criteria depending on the attribute type:
		<ul class="list-group mb-5 m-3 gap-2">
			<li>
				A Text attribute is filtered with %TXT% (Filters everything that contains the letters TXT)
			</li>
			<li>		
				A numeric attribute is filtered with a sign and a value (e.g., Stock quantity: > 5)
			</li>
		</ul>
	</p>

	<h3 class="fw-bold text-dark my-4">Notifications</h3>
	<p class="fs-5 fw-light w-sm-75">
		Notifications allow you to be alerted by email after each addition and modification of an object in a collection.  
		They can be configured for each collection and each attribute.
		<br><br>
		Example: Be alerted when an object in the 'Interventions' collection has an attribute 'Status' equal to 'Completed'.
	</p>

	<h3 class="fw-bold text-dark my-4">Users ands Teams</h3>
	<p class="fs-5 fw-light w-sm-75">
		You can create users and include them in a team.
		<br>
		A team has access to certain information defined in the filters.
		<br>
		For each team, it is possible to have a filter for each collection.
		<br>
		If no filter is assigned to a collection for a team, that team will not see the collection.
	</p>


